"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:11.6.2.2\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">11.6.2.2</span> Kodrantes</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">κοδράντης</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(kodrantēs)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt5:26\">MAT 5:26</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark12:42\">MRK 12:42</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/UBS-0038_kodrantes.jpg\" alt=\"Tiberian quadrans or kodrantes, similar to a penny\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Tiberian quadrans or kodrantes, similar to a penny (© Kwo-Wei Peng by United Bible Societies)</figcaption></figure>Kodrantes:</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt5:26\">MAT 5:26</a>: At the end of this verse most translations have something like “until you have paid the last penny” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>). It is also possible to express this well without naming a specific coin; for example, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Century Version\">NCV</abbr> and PV say “until you have paid everything you owe.” Some scholars think it more likely, however, more likely that this clause means “until you have paid off all the money the judge fined you [or, said you must pay].” Compare <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>, which reads “until you pay the last penny of your fine” (similarly <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"God&#x27;s Word Translation\">GW</abbr>).</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark12:42\">MRK 12:42</a>: At the end of this verse the Greek says literally “two lepta, which are a kodrantes.” Many translations expand “two lepta” somewhat to “two small copper coins” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Century Version\">NCV</abbr>), and then indicate that they were worth very little by saying they were worth “a penny” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>), “a few cents” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Century Version\">NCV</abbr>), “less than a cent” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"God&#x27;s Word Translation\">GW</abbr>), “about a penny” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>), or “of very low value” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Spanish Common Language Version (Dios Habla Hoy)\">SPCL</abbr>). <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Italian Common Language Version\">ITCL</abbr> omits the second phrase, since the purpose of that phrase in the original text was to explain to Mark’s readers the value of the lesser known <em>lepton</em>.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
